  "referred_to_by": [
    {
      "type": "LinguisticObject",
      "content": "A six-volume folio **composite atlas** (*atlas factice*) published in Amsterdam by the firm of Reinier Ottens (1698–1750) and Josua Ottens (1704–1765), c.1725–1750. The Ottens brothers were among the most prominent map publishers of 18th-century Amsterdam, heirs to the firm founded by their father Joachim Ottens (1663–1719). The *Atlas Major* is not a conventionally authored work with a fixed text: it belongs to the tradition of the made-to-order luxury atlas, assembled on commission from maps by many different cartographers (F. de Wit, G. de L'Isle, H. Jaillot, N. Visscher, J.B. Homann, G. van Keulen, P. Schenk, and many others), all engraved and hand-colored. No two copies are identical. Known configurations range from 2 to 15 volumes. The Teylers copy is six volumes.",
      "classified_as": [
